review_blob:
Hazy yellow more orange than pilsner. Light, sticky lacing over persistently covering, thin head.
Aroma of orange, stone fruit, and dank hops. Taste is same with a hint of artificial sweetener. 
Body is thin.
Finish is bitter with sticky lips.

Draught. Copper colored pilsner appetizing covering lacing likes sticking high on the glass. Aroma is coconut with hint of lemon. Sweet/bitter flavor is cloyingly sweet coconut biscuit which fades to sweet coconut wine and thence to a naturally appetizing cane finishing with hop bitter in the back. Body is thick and sticky. 
Overall, stimulating for the coconovelty but too heavy on the front end.

Bomber. Amber/pilsner makes copper color under a lingering eggshell -color head and slow, sticky lacing. Aroma is delicious hoppy pilsner with strong hints of roasty caramel/carmalization and floral/herbal. Flavor is bitter/sour, and that taste lingers through the longish, rather astringent finish (washing out other flavors in the mouth leaving the simple beer flavor) - except to settle on a butterscotch, charred peppery candy / scotch whiskey character. Palate is pilsner profile, slightly peppy carbonation, and a little creamy sticky in feeling. Overall, another fine Sudwerk to enjoy.
UPDATED: JUN 14, 2015
beer_name: Anchor Zymaster Series No. 8: Luxardo Cherry Ale

review_blob:
Draught. Mahogony body under thick sandy lacing. 
Small aroma a little coffee and candy.
Taste is first and most and last in the caliente. But there is sweetness. Not candy. Natural light wood and malt sweet smokiness - just a foreshadow of the deep chocolate that that you trace back to a primordial cocoa forest that settles oh so slowly on your tongue.  Palate is up to the trip.
Finish is, did I mention the caliente?  Its a big, woody pepper - not a sharp little snake bite.  If youre looking for cocoa puff, you got the wrong beer.  Character and class.
UPDATED: JAN 21, 2015

Bomber.
Hazy red coffee body under fast-dissolving brown-tinged white head and frosty lacing.
Aroma is roasted coffee ground and chocolate toffee, some leather and wood, and hint of cough drop or soy sauce for undertone. But its got a garbage funkiness or tang. Maybe its just me.
Flavor is coffee bitter and mild sweet and umami.
Palate is a bit thin and slightly fizzy with a coffee bitter long finish.
Overall weaker than some but at only 5.4% maybe the lowest, and for that, its pretty good, but there are better.

Opaque body under fast lacing and sandy, foamy head that dissolves in a couple of minutes.
Aroma is mild roast, dark chocolate cake, cereal, and fudge toffee.
Taste is salt and bitter and very mildly cough drop sweet.
Palate is a little fizzy if not rough. Finish is bitter like espresso.
Overall good beer.

Draught. Opaque body with no head or lacing. Aroma of coffee percolator water and roasted coffee and roasted cocoa. Taste a bit too sweet but classy bitterness. Palate disappointingly thin. Good, addictive beer.
beer_name: Brewfist / Prairie Artisan Ales Spaghetti Western

review_blob: Very persistent and solid mineral colored head over nearly opaque mahogany body. Aroma of toasted biscuit and roasted cocoa and sophisticated and delicate like a French chef took a shot at making cocoa puffs. Mmmm. Taste is bitter on the order of coffee or dark chocolate. Body is disappointingly thin. But the board said only 5% whereas its listed at 6.5%, here. Its a solid beer but Im not getting the ultra.

22oz bomber. Appetizing slushy sandy, brown head and lacing over mahogany body. Head dissolves fairly shortly. Aroma of banana and roast coffee. Taste as above with umami, a little chickory and cough drop and some woody. Not sweet. Very good. 
Body is medium full with some sticky creaminess and a long, mild bitter finish. 
Overall, this is a class crafting to seek.

On tap at Beachwood BBQ LB. From memory. Not a lot of head or lacing over a hazy orange tinted body. Aroma is citrus and spice much like a saison. Taste is a little salty/sour//bitter/sweet from the spice. Mild but clear.  Palate is a little thick but not for a beer thats a pie. Its key lime pie with graham cracker crust in a glass with milder flavor but quite satisfying.

Bomber bottle. Persistent thin white covering over amberish yellow body and lacing fast and wispy. A bit of old grocery funk in the aroma that the citra seems calculated to disguise or balance. Taste is mild salt, bitter. Palate is clean, and fairly fresh, astringent like fruit juice with a thin creamy finish. Seems a fine sample of an American Pale Ale. Not my style with a bit too much hops, but Im not sure of the dynamic of its role in this brew.
UPDATED: FEB 16, 2014

Appearance is small, dissolving, brown sandy head with fast brown lacing over a mahogany barely translucent body. Aroma is coffee and chocolate coca cola. Taste is mildly sweet. Palate is soft with some cream. Finish is coffee/dark chocolate bitter. Classy.
beer_name: Six Rivers Paradise Moon Coffee Porter

review_blob:
Congregation tap. Dissolving head over moderately frosty lacing and hazy, yellow-orange body appetizing like a tropical fruit drink. 
Aroma of sour beer (like most sours) with some fruit candy sweetness.
Taste is sour with hint of natural sweetness.
The finish has a presence of salt and bitter. 
Palate is fruit-juice astringent to mouth but thick-jucily coating the tongue. Effervescence most prominent in throat instead of on tongue. Very good.
UPDATED: JAN 20, 2014

750ml bomber from Whole Foods. Slightly hazy pekoe tea body under minimal white sandy head and scanty lacing mmm babe.
Aroma of malty funk and white stone fruit and spicy hops and maybe brown bread.  Cocoa powder presence as it warms.  
Tastes mildly sweet from fruit and mildly salty and medium bitter from the hops. Its an herbal hops - not very biting like pine.
This blend needs effervescence, and this one brings it well, and I like the feel and how it enhances the beer. Not stinging but effective.
Overall effect is pleasantly woody (like a barrel).
beer_name: Anchor Zymaster Series No. 5 Harvest One American Pale Ale

review_blob:
500ml bottle. Appears as hazy pekoe tea with little head and frosty, sticky lacing that runs in ten seconds. Aroma is herbal hoppy and malty. Simple and pleasant without cardboard or funk but woody. Taste is mildly bitter. 
Palate is slightly flat soda water, light and thin with a slightly oily bitter finish. Overall, its not bad but not worth seeking.

Bottle like the picture 1pt 6oz. Pilsner-like, white thin but fully-covering head over a clear, golden body and some lacing lines. Aroma is quite hoppy and a little peppery. Taste is salty. Finish has a peppery and hoppy bite. Body is quite full. Overall, beer is well-balanced and a first-class craft.

650ml (22oz) bottle.  Short-lasting red dirty white sandy  head over slightly hazy amber body with lots of distinct effervescent bubbles disappearing at the nearly headless top.  Lacing is frosty for a few seconds.
Aroma is a fairly commercial cereal malt and fresh but otherwise unimpressive.
Taste is light sweetness, medium bitterness, with a hint of umami satisfaction.  It is adequate but not compelling.
Body is a bit full and light oily or heavy creamy in the mouth with a clean finish except for lingering bitterness in the back of the mouth.  
It is a low-abv red lager that I would not avoid and can recommend for sharing but would not want to drink a second in one night in lieu of any other good lager.

8oz draught.  Beige head dissolves in a minute to a thin covering over a rust and coppery body which a direct backlight reveals is really a pleasing ruby red.  Aroma is fresh red berries like raspberry and strawberry some being tart (as in not quite ripe) and fresh apple - really appetizing if you like tart fruit.  Taste is salty with mild sweetness and sourness and mild bitterness.  There is a not-too-subtle bitter finish.  Palate is lively, fine carbonation like soda pop (not the taste - the feel).  This is a very well-crafted beer.
UPDATED: NOV 9, 2014

12oz bottle pours a two-finger sandy head that dissolves in a minute over a deep brown translucent body with frosty lacing.  
Aroma is bread and toasted grain, some basement earth and hints of dark chocolate and dried berry.  
Taste is mild salty and lightly sweet and umami with a lingering bitter finish.
Body is full with strong carbonation and thick texture that leaves a sticky residue.
A superb beer with extra points for organic ingredients.

12oz bottle like the picture.  Coffee-foam head dissolves quickly to thin cover with frosty but very fast lacing over a nearly opaque mahogany body.  Aroma is tea, chocolate toffee, roasted coffee and pepper and little or no smoke.  But the taste delivers the sweet and bitter smoke and the pepper.  Finish is peppery spicy and lingering.  Body is medium/full.  Overall very good.

Draught at Congregation.  Persistent tan sandy head over nearly opaque mahogany body and clinging, frosty, sandy lacing.  Aroma is roasted chicory, coffee and herb.  Taste is a quite bitter and a bit sweet and a pinch salty - mostly bitter.  Palate has a lingering, mild bitter finish, fuzzy but astringent like coffee or tea.  Body is medium full.  Overall, a very good session stout that promotes relaxed contemplation - unlike most beers.

Draught in 10oz flute.  Hazy golden body under clinging head and lacing.  Aroma is of ripe and sour berry with a hop bite that carries freshness of berries.  Taste is, in order of experience, salt, sweet, and sour - all of equal strength.  Finish is sour that lingers.  Body is medium and clean to maybe a little sticky with a fruit-juice full finish.  Healthy.

Tulip glass draught.  Hazy golden body under clinging, persistent head and lacing.  Aroma is good, sweet spices and hoppy carrying a peppery nose.  Taste is mildly sweet with a mildly sweet and even milder bitter medium finish.  Interesting session saison for its spice and savor.

Tap at Congregation.  Instantly dissolving off-white head over fast lacing and a very hazy, dark, yellow/orange body.  Aroma is of smoked fish and banana malted candy.  Taste is sweet and salty like old world candy and very good.  I have low tolerance for sweeteners - and this beer is not close to being cloying.  It is exemplary as a craftsmans use of spice.  Very clean and classy.  Finish is abrupt but sweet through and through from tip of tongue through the last.  Well-balanced and subtle.  This is a very very good saison.

Tap at Congregation.  White head dissolves in five minutes over fast lacing and a clear, pilsner body.  Aroma is pilsner mild but straw, grass, and some process of baking whole grain bread or urine.  Taste is mildly sweet becoming water with a long, mild bitter finish.  There is mild umami somewhere between the aroma and the finish.  Overall, very good, but there are better.

Bomber.  Whitish head quickly dissolves to spotty thin covering with fast lacing over a hazy light lager body.  Aroma is nobles "Liberty" hops and allspice and clove.  Seriously spicy.  Flavor is quite soda pop sweet.  Fuzzy finish of long sweet with slight bitter.  Spicily crafted lager.  Commendable but Ill pass.
beer_name: Noble Ale Works / Cismontane Golden State Lager

review_blob: Tap at Congregation.  Slightly hazy apple-juice body right for pale ale with one-finger head dissolving in less than five minutes leaving no lacing.  Aroma very light, sour, rotting straw.  Bitter taste up front with mild sour finish.  Very light overall.  Extra point for rye.

Tap at Congregation.  Quick dissolving white head over a hazy yellow body thats a bit light for saison and many rings of lacing.  Aroma is rain-soaked earth and clover.  Taste is salty with a sweet aftertaste and a short finish.  This is a mild, fuller-bodied, great beer.

Nice head that dissolves to a thin covering with a few clouds of foam over a copper body that is a little too particulate to be pretty.  Nose is hosey watery and good for a lager with flavors of nuts and caramel - a lager with character.  Taste is cough drop gentle and definite: a little hoppiness emerging from the malt.  Palate is at least medium if not full for a lager with perfect carbonation and appropriate finish for the taste: it lingers and slowly fades.  A good commercial beer that I wouldnt hesitate to have.

Tap.  Slight white head dissolving quickly to a thin covering over a pilsner-colored body darkend by bourbon barrel wood but clear.  Aroma is bourbon, straw, chocolate, and cracked grain with pretzel in the mix.  Taste is sour and salty.  Palate is lively with effervescence rather quick in the finish.  Overall, a good beer though rather forward with bourbon at only 6%.  Kind of a Disneyland night on the town.
A hazy, yeasty, body.  Not unappealing nose.  Not too sweet with a slightly bitter finish.  Good beer.

Tap at Congregation.  Cherry aroma.  No head.  Red body with attractive translucence.  Taste is cherry and not too vinous (I dont like vinous) but a little.  Thin body like wine with good carbonation like champagne.

8oz draught on nitro.  Thick, foamy, sugary head a bit brownish with yellow tints and similar but quicker lacing over a vibrant reddish body.  Aroma is very nutty and a hint of vanilla.  Taste is mildly sweet and bitter.  Palate is very nitro smooth.  Body is very light.  Finish is fairly long and almond bitter.  Very good beer from a small, local brewery with nice folks.

Draught.  Rootbeer-float-foamy head persists for ten minutes with creamy lacing over an dark amber body.  Aroma is umami, smoke, and produce.  Taste is umami and bitter.  Palate is light and creamy with fine and lively carbonation.  Excellent rauchbier

22oz bottle @ 7.5% abv.  Mahogony body is barely translucent under a fast-dissolving dusty head with some large bubbles and thickish lacing that runs fairly fast.  Not a very impressive appearance.  Aroma is mouth-watering roasted chocolate and not choking but light with maybe a hint of smoke.  Taste delivers more than a hint of smoke and I like.  Taste is mostly umami, mildly sweet and bitter.  Palate is medium easy thick and creamy with average carbonation and a nice, bitter finish.  A pretty good lager smoked porter.

Bottle.  Off-white brown fine sandy head floats like a cloud and then dissolves in about ten minutes over a clear brown body with foamy lacing.
Aroma is wet dough, funk, roast malt, toast, raisin.  
Taste is mild sweet, salt, and bitter with a hint of umami and delivers the dark, ripe, fruit aroma.
Palate is a nice, coarse feel, with a classy medium full body.  So texture is thick with lively carbonation and a medium slightly bitter finish.
I like Ayinger; and this Altbairisch Dunkel is very good at only 5% abv.

2012 Bomber Bottle.  Dirty sandy head of fine and large bubbles dissolves in five minutes to a thin covering with foamy lacing over a bronze body.  As the beer warms up to room temp, the lacing and foam appear as cold coffee - gone.  So the allure fades.  Aroma is floral and herbal hoppy with roast malt with a little grocery produce funk and hints of fruit like banana and those of a trippel.  Taste is sweet with mild salt and grows bitter.  Finish is medium though mild bitterness lingers longly - almost pharm-like.  Body is light except full in the center and a bit puckering on the bitter buds of the tongue.  Interesting palate.  Overall an OK beer.  Firestone doesnt do much to hold my enthusiasm.

Draught pint.  Black and opaque body.  Nose is roast coffee and toffee.  Taste delivers the nose well also umami and sweet and salty rum.  Carbonation is medium.  Body is medium light.  Bitterness lingers on the palate.  Stone is best with smokes and stouts.  Very good, here, but not the best of theirs.

Draught.  No head with lacing that varries from full cover to thin and runny all over a dark red nearly opaque body.  Nose is umami smoke, wood, and soap.  Taste is salty and umami.  Good, medium strong, carbonation.  Body is medium full.  Finish is pleasantly a continuation of the taste that fades like a good meal.  Excellent.
UPDATED: JAN 25, 2014

12oz Cask.  Head color of citrus zest dissolves in three minutes to a partial foamy covering with some big soapy bubbles and lastly to lovely pond scum all over an amber with haze body.  Notes are hoppy and bitter citrus with lavvender soap.  Taste is medium bitter.  Carbonation and body are medium to light.  Finish is long and bitter.  Not much "oaked" about it but decent overall.

Pint draught listed at 5% abv.  Sandy head dissolves in five minutes to a thin covering over a dark red body with thick, frosty, covering lacing.  Nose is slightly vinegary.  Taste is bitter band aid.  Carbonation is fine and lively.  Body is light.  A porter with some craftsmanship and character.

16oz draught.  Half-finger, light brown sandy head dissolves in ten minutes over an opaque body and leaving a light, lacing ring.  Aroma is chocolate, milky and classy - not faux coco puffs - with light roast.  Taste is mildly sweet with a hint of salt and a bitter chocolate finish.  Very light bodied with fine carbonation that is of medium to light volume with a slightly creamy palate.  Overall, definitely better than Youngs and slightly better than Left-Hand Milk Stout.

12oz bottle.  Coffee-colored head lasts a flash and flattens to nothing but sticky lacing in seconds over an opaque body passing light on the edges.  Aroma is mild cherry bomb with classy vinous notes that stay tamely with the beer so not vinous and more bready like good cherry bread (not pop tart) without nuts and a hint of alcohol.  Taste is bitter cherry roasted bread.  Body is medium and slightly sticky.  Finish is mildly bitter.  Overall, a good beer.

12oz draught.  No head.  Muddy with little luminescence.  Lacing is full.  Aroma is chocolate, caramel, and hot pepper spice with note of light popsicle stick.  Theres not much alcohol going on for a 9%er.  Taste delivers aroma and is mildly sweet.  Palate is thin and clean with little finish.  Overall this is the coating of a candied apple and so good.
beer_name: New Belgium Lips of Faith - Cocoa Mole
